  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the causes for receding gums?",
  "response": "Receding gums, also known as gingival recession, occur when the gum tissue surrounding the teeth wears away or pulls back, exposing more of the tooth or its root. Several factors can contribute to receding gums:\n\n### 1. **Poor Oral Hygiene**\n   - Inadequate brushing and flossing can lead to plaque buildup, which hardens into tartar. This can cause gum inflammation (gingivitis) and eventually periodontal disease, leading to gum recession.\n\n### 2. **Aggressive Brushing**\n   - Brushing your teeth too hard or using a hard-bristled toothbrush can erode gum tissue and damage the enamel, contributing to recession.\n\n### 3. **Gum Disease (Periodontitis)**\n   - Advanced stages of gum disease destroy the gum tissue and the bone that supports the teeth, leading to gum recession.\n\n### 4. **Genetics**\n   - Some people are more prone to gum disease and gum recession due to their genetic makeup, regardless of their oral hygiene habits.\n\n### 5. **Hormonal Changes**\n   - Hormonal fluctuations during puberty, pregnancy, or menopause can make gums more sensitive and vulnerable to recession.\n\n### 6. **Tobacco Use**\n   - Smoking or chewing tobacco can lead to plaque buildup and reduce the blood supply to the gums, increasing the risk of recession.\n\n### 7. **Teeth Grinding (Bruxism)**\n   - Grinding or clenching your teeth can put excessive pressure on the gums, causing them to recede over time.\n\n### 8. **Misaligned Teeth or Bite Issues**\n   - Crooked teeth or an uneven bite can place excess force on certain gums, leading to recession.\n\n### 9. **Lip or Tongue Piercings**\n   - Jewelry in piercings can rub against the gums, causing irritation and recession over time.\n\n### 10. **Aging**\n   - The risk of gum recession increases with age, as gum tissue naturally becomes thinner and more susceptible to damage.\n\n### 11. **Trauma or Injury**\n   - Physical trauma to the gums, such as from an accident or dental procedure, can cause recession.\n\n### 12. **Medical Conditions**\n   - Certain systemic diseases like diabetes or conditions that affect the immune system can increase the risk of gum disease and recession.\n\n### 13. **Medications**\n   - Some medications, such as those that cause dry mouth, can contribute to gum recession by reducing saliva production and increasing plaque buildup.\n\n### Prevention and Treatment\n   - Maintain good oral hygiene with regular brushing, flossing, and dental checkups.\n   - Use a soft-bristled toothbrush and gentle brushing technique.\n   - Address teeth grinding with a nightguard.\n   - Quit smoking or using tobacco products.\n   - Seek treatment for misaligned teeth or bite issues.\n   - If recession is severe, a dentist may recommend treatments such as scaling and root planing, gum grafts, or other procedures to restore gum health.\n\nIf you notice signs of receding gums, such as tooth sensitivity, longer-looking teeth, or exposed roots, consult a dentist for an evaluation and appropriate treatment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
